      &ldquo;The ATE program gave me the skills to make better choices.&rdquo;
    </p>

    <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align: left;">Skipping <span>Out</span></h2>
    <p style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8;">
      Mark was missing more school than he was attending. By the middle of his sophomore year, he had earned a reputation: short fuse, quick to walk out, slow to come back. Teachers had stopped calling on him. His mom was running out of ideas. The school was running out of patience.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8;">
      Instead of suspension, Mark&rsquo;s school referred him to Reach For Youth&rsquo;s ATE Program &mdash; a structured, evidence-based intervention that helps youth build emotional regulation, conflict resolution, and decision-making skills.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align: left;">Naming the <span>Feeling</span></h2>
    <p style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8;">
      The first thing the ATE facilitator did was hand Mark a sheet of paper with a list of feelings on it. He looked at it like it was a trick. He&rsquo;d been called &ldquo;angry&rdquo; his whole life. But that was the only word anyone had ever given him.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8;">
      Over the next twelve weeks, Mark learned to name what was actually going on underneath the anger &mdash; embarrassed, overwhelmed, hungry, ignored, scared. He learned how to pause before reacting. He learned what his body was telling him before his fists did.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align: left;">Practicing the <span>New Way</span></h2>
    <p style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8;">
      Change didn&rsquo;t happen overnight. Mark still had bad days. But he had something he hadn&rsquo;t had before: tools, and an adult who believed he could use them. His attendance climbed. His grades pulled up to passing, then better than passing. He stayed in his seat through frustration he would have walked out of a year before.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align: left;">On <span>Track</span></h2>
    <p style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8;">
      Mark is set to graduate on time. He has a part-time job at a hardware store and is exploring a trade program after high school. He still uses the breathing exercise his ATE facilitator taught him &mdash; sometimes in the school hallway, sometimes in the break room at work, sometimes just at home before he texts his mom back.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-primary); font-weight: 600; text-align: center; margin-top: var(--space-2xl); padding: var(--space-xl); background: rgba(114,242,206,0.15); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
      &ldquo;ATE didn&rsquo;t change who I am. It gave me a way to be who I am without burning everything down.&rdquo;
    </p>

